2016 Race Photos from Erin Bibeau Photography
2015 Race Photos from Erin Bibeau Photography
Your first view of the Nokhu Crags from the start of the Never Summer 100k.
There is a very good chance for moose encounters on the Never Summer 100k course.
After a short warm up on the Gould and Seven Utes jeep roads, the course heads straight up a steep and rough logging road.
The first view from the summit of Seven Utes looking north towards Diamond Peak and the Rawahs.
The view of the Nokhu Crags from the summit of Seven Utes.
The view of the Never Summers from the summit of Seven Utes.
The Silver Creek trail follows the shoulder of Braddock.
Looking north towards Diamond and the Rawahs from the Silver Creek trail.
A view of the Silver Creek trail back towards the shoulder of Braddock.
The approach to Lake Agnes follows some rough old logging roads.
Wildflowers and views from the approach to Lake Agnes.
The route to Lake Agnes may be a bit rough but the scenery is incredible!
Views from the Lake Agnes shoreline.
More views from the Lake Agnes shoreline.
More views from the Lake Agnes shoreline.
The route leaves Lake Agnes directly under the Nokhu Crags.
The wooden Michigan Ditch pipeline was constructed in the late 1800's to divert water to the front range.
The Michigan Ditch road offers a few "easy" miles on the course ...at 10,000ft.
The American Lakes trail climbs up from the Michigan Ditch on the east side of the Nokhu Crags.
Below the Nokhu Crags on the American Lakes trail.
Another view back to the Nokhu Crags from the American Lakes trail.
The high point at the top of the American Lakes trail.
Dropping down into the American Lakes basin.
The route passes by the Michigan Lakes.
Views from the jeep road on the way out of the American Lakes basin.
Views from the summit of North Diamond. Longs Peak is visible far to the south.
The route follows the ridge line all the way to Montgomery Pass.
A view back towards North Diamond from Montgomery Pass.
The Yurt Trail connects Montgomery Pass road to Ruby Jewel.
The Yurt Trail is pretty rough in spots. Don't lose sight of the trail and course markings here.
The Yurt Trail crosses several gorgeous meadows. Footing is rough and the weeds and flowers may be waist high by race day.
The Yurt Trail also crosses a couple large clear cuts. There may not be much climbing on the Yurt trail but it's still one of the more challenging segments of the course.
The Ruby Jewel road is as rough, rocky, and technical as most trails.
The Hidden Valley trail gradually climbs to Kelly Lake.
You can see all the way back to the Nokhu Crags from the high point on the Hidden Valley trail.
Looking down onto Kelly Lake and north to the Rawahs.
There may still be snow fields above Kelly Lake on race day.
Some gorgeous single track on the descent down from Kelly Lake.
A huge aspen grove at the bottom of the Kelly Lake trail.
The last major climb on the course follows a rough trail up to Clear Lake.
The view west from the Clear Lake trail. Runners at the back of the pack will be treated to a spectacular sunset.
Clear Lake tucked under South Rawah Peak. Definitely worth the climb.
The trail back from Clear Lake follows the western border of the park in and out of aspen groves and sage brush.
Wide open views to the west of the Clear Lake trail.
The Lumberjack crosses open meadows in the center of the park. Runners who make it through here in daylight will be treated to views from the Never Summers to the Rawahs.
The last section back to the highway follows some very rough old logging roads.
An open clear cut offers some final views to the north.
One last view of the Never Summers on the road back down to the highway crossing.
